data.content:
# Migrating `BackgroundProcessor` to .NET 8

## Critical Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Removed entirely** |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it could corrupt process state by interrupting code at arbitrary points (inside locks, during I/O, mid-write). Your `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` handler only *appeared* safe — it could itself be aborted.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class BackgroundProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<WorkItem> _channel;
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public BackgroundProcessor(int capacity = 128)
    {
        _channel = Channel.CreateBounded<WorkItem>(new BoundedChannelOptions(capacity)
        {
            FullMode = BoundedChannelFullMode.Wait
        });
    }

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    public ValueTask EnqueueAsync(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        return _channel.Writer.WriteAsync(item, ct);
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            try
            {
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, ct);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — roll back then exit cleanly
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                await FlushBuffersAsync();
            }
        }
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryComplete();          // signal no more items
        _cts.Cancel();                           // cancel in-flight work

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Graceful timeout, then observe completion
            try
            {
                await _workerTask.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
            }
            catch (TimeoutException)
            {
                // Worker didn't stop in time — already cancelled, just log
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Expected
            }
        }

        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Migration Pitfalls

**1. `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationToken` is not 1:1**

Abort interrupted *anywhere*, even inside blocking calls like `Monitor.Enter` or unmanaged code. `CancellationToken` is **cooperative** — your blocking calls must accept and check the token:

```csharp
// ❌ Won't respond to cancellation
var data = socket.Receive(buffer);

// ✅ Responds to cancellation
var data = await socket.ReceiveAsync(buffer, ct);
```

**2. `Thread.Sleep` in `Stop()` was hiding a race condition**

The original code had no guarantee the thread would finish within 2 seconds. The migrated version uses `Channel.Complete()` to drain naturally, plus `CancellationToken` for hard stop — no arbitrary sleeps.

**3. `volatile bool` → `CancellationToken`**

`volatile bool` can't wake a blocked thread. `CancellationToken` can cancel pending `ReadAllAsync`, `Task.Delay`, and any async I/O that accepts it.

**4. `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks become dead code silently**

.NET 8 won't warn you — the catch block simply never executes. Audit every `catch (ThreadAbortException)` in your codebase; move cleanup logic to `OperationCanceledException` handlers or `finally` blocks.

**5. `IAsyncDisposable` replaces manual `Stop()`**

This integrates with `await using`, preventing resource leaks:
```csharp
await using var processor = new BackgroundProcessor();
processor.Start();
// automatically drained and stopped at end of scope
```

## Quick Audit Checklist

```bash
# Find all Thread.Abort / ResetAbort / ThreadAbortException in your codebase
grep -rn "Thread\.Abort\|ResetAbort\|ThreadAbortException" --include="*.cs" .
```

Every hit is a mandatory migration point in .NET 8.
